e Holocaust and World History: Raphael Lemkin and Comparative Methodology -- tSelect Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last two decades our empirical knowledge of the Holocaust has been vastly expanded. Yet this empirical blossoming has not been accompanied by much theoretical reflection on the historiography. This volume argues that reflection on the historical process of (re)constructing the past is as important for understanding the Holocaust—and, by extension, any past event—as is archival research. It aims to go beyond the dominant paradigm of political history and describe the emergence of methods now being used to reconstruct the past in the context of Holocaust historiography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aBergen, Doris L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloxham, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConfino, Alon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinchelstein, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedländer, Saul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Amos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKansteiner, Wulf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoses, A. Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoyn, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeumann, Boaz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRupnow, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary